		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />ok that clarified my doubt. thx.
<br />
<br />I have another question:
<br />
<br />- Suppose we have ran 112 cpu cyles (112 * 341 = 336 ppu cycles) and the next instruction takes 4 cycles (12 ppu cycles). Results in:
<br />
<br />336 cc + 12 cc = 348 cc !! (ppu cycles)
<br />
<br />so taking into account that we start at "0" (zero), then 348 - 340 = 8 ppu Cycles.
<br />
<br />What do i do with that "overflow" do i use that remaining ppu cycles for the next scanline or i throw it away and i start again with "0"?.
<br />
<br />Thanks in advance.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Disch</b> [ Tue Aug 30, 2005 2:14 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You must keep that overflow -- not only between scanlines, but also between frames.  CPU cycles will more often than not "spill" into the next frame and will almost always spill into the next scanline.  Cutting off that overflow will give the CPU several "free" cycles (more than it would get on the real system) -- so games which rely on timing will mess up.
<br />
<br />So:
<br />
<br />"do i use that remaining ppu cycles for the next scanline"   &lt;--- yes
<br />
<br />"i throw it away and i start again with "0"?"  &lt;---  no

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


