	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Anes wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">when exactly mmc3 slcounter is hited?</div><br /><br />On the rising edge (0 -&gt; 1) of the PPU A12 line -- but only if it's been low for several (at least 9) PPU cycles.  Under "normal" conditions this occurs:<br /><br />- when the game changes the PPU address to flip on bit 12 from an off state ($0xxx -&gt; $1xxx)<br /><br />- on cycle 260 in the scanline (the first sprite CHR fetch)<br /><br /><br />For the nitty gritty details (if you want a super-accurate counter), you'll have to be familair with what fetches the PPU makes and when.  BT's ppu doc is a good reference:<br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://nesdev.com/2C02%20technical%20reference.TXT">http://nesdev.com/2C02%20techn ... erence.TXT</a><!-- m --><br /><br />Although the info in that doc which actually discusses the MMC3 counter is wrong (he says A13 when it's really A12)<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Is it the 6502 "nmos programming manual" a good source to extract from it the cpu cycles?.</div>
<br />
<br />This doc is always good:
<br />
<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.obelisk.demon.co.uk/6502/reference.html">http://www.obelisk.demon.co.uk/6502/reference.html</a><!-- m -->
<br />
<br />Or if you want details on which bytes are read/written on which cycles... the section near the bottom of this doc is great:
<br />
<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://nesdev.com/6502_cpu.txt">http://nesdev.com/6502_cpu.txt</a><!-- m -->

		

